<br>
When you join a group, *ask* who is the Primary healer, the secondary healer, the puller and the primary tank. If the people in the group don't know the answers to those questions, leave the group. I am not joking. Turn and go. If you really really want to stay, then take control and organize the group. I am warning you tho, they probably won't listen and you probably will die.<br>
<br>
<br>
The primary healer: Heals .. that is all. He does not melee, swinging his or her feeble mace like a flea itching an elephant, he does not cast DD or DOT; the primary healer sits down during the fight and stands up only to heal. Anticipate the 3rd bubble of life and heal as the level crosses over it. Don't wait until your tanks are down to 2 bubbs, heal as they enter 3 bubbs. If something unforseen happens, and your tank is at two <br>
<br>
bubbs you will never heal in time and a Paladin will have to blow LoH to save someone you should have been healing. When you have TWO G Heals left in you, call LOM (low on mana) to let your secondary healer know it's time for them to take over. Sit down and med. Do not run up to the mob and start flailing away in a pitiful, ineffective fashion. You MIGHT do 100pts of dmg over the course of a whole fight, your tank is doing <br>
that amount per ROUND. Sit down and do your own job. An excellent secondary task for the Prime Healer is <br>
watching for wandering mobs coming in to spoil your day. If you see one, yell it a LOT; tell the tanks to pull the mob out of the path of the wanderer. Lastly, heal from a distance. Hate List is distance-dependent. the farther you are from the mob, the less impact your actions have. If you stand next to a mob and heal the <br>
tanks, you go right to the top of the hate list. Stand back near max heal range and heal and I can assure you that very seldom will a mob agro on you unless you are healing way too fast.<br>
<br>
<br>
The secondary healer: Works their defensive and offensive magic until they have two bubbs of mana left, and then RESERVES those two bubbs for healing. Also, if the primary healer is not careful, their heals will pull a mob off of the tanks and onto themselves. It is the secondary healer's job to KEEP the primary healer alive while he or she is being pummelled, until the tanks can regain control of the mob. Damage shield the tanks, <br>
do your DOT or DD but reserve the proper mana for heals, and watch for the LOM signal from the primary. Also watch for the ON ME call from the primary, which is yelled when a mob is on them, and they can not heal.<br>
<br>
<br>
The puller: can make or break a party. If your puller is an overanxious nitwit with the attention span of a 10 year old after a case of Pixie Sticks who is hell bent on killing you all by ignoring the pleas of the casters that they are LOM or OOM then tell him point blank to sit down, or he is leaving the group. The puller in a group is NOT the person who is tired of sitting around and wants some exp NOW, this person is very <br>
dangerous and in their blind haste will kill you all and then blame you for not keeping him healed. You have <br>
all been there, and I hope you have the will to not go there again by telling this person to stop. A good puller is a highly skilled individual, who can gauge the strength of the party and that of the mobs and pull the appropriate mob for the situation; harder mobs for a party which is FM and rested, and easier mobs for parties which are combat ready but not at their full power. Primary healer will have the puller targetted as <br>
they return IN CASE they seriously need a heal. Dont' heal if it's not serious, since a heal this early will pull <br>
the mob to the healer in a heartbeat. As a puller, wait for the right moment to pull. If your party can not handle two mobs then WAIT until there is only one mob which can agro on you. This is not a race to see who can pull (read 'die') the fastest; your party is counting on you to safely pull for them at a decent rate. <br>
When the puller arrives back at the group, run behind the tanks and stand there. DO NOT squeeal and run in <br>
circles like a little greased piggy. Stand there and take the beating until the tanks gain control over the mob. The healers will keep you alive if you have allowed them to have mana by pulling at a proper rate. btw, this is why healers DONT PULL. It helps if the person pulling can track ... and a puller really should not be <br>
running right up to a mob and cracking him in the shin to get his attention. Bow pull or stun pull .. snare pull .. shuriken, whatever .. get the mob's attention from a distance. Let the party know you have incoming. CASTERS do not stand up on Incoming unless you are FM. Sit there and med until the mob actually arrives.<br>
<br>
<br>
Main Tank: is the person which does the most damage a round and is hopefully prepared to take the most damage. If you are swinging dual Ykeshas and your taunt skill is 200 you have to know that a mob is going to want YOU dead dead dead. You are his personal demon and he will do his damndest to kill you. It helps a party greatly if one person is taking most of the damage. The healers can concentrate on this one person <br>
and easily keep that person alive if their AC is high enough for the job. If you have a caster in your party who likes to stand up close and DD and melee then that person is WASTING your heal power because he or she does not have the armor class rating to be up there and will take astounding damage and effort to keep him alive. The main tank will stop taunting and kicking if they reach two bubbs of life. This will hopefully <br>
allow another tank who is healthier to take over as the main target. This is referred to as &quot;bouncing&quot; a mob. When you are low on hitpoints, back off a little and let another tank take control of the mob as the healers take care of you. If you are a healing-class tank like a Paladin, then learn to heal yourself or others while  in combat. Bounce the mob to another tank, step back a little and cast heal then rejoin combat. Do this only in emergencies. If the tanks have to take time to heal, the situation is very grim. Its very important to assist the main tank. If possible everyone should be working on the SAME mob at once. Use the /assist command, targetted on your main tank. <br>
<br>
<br>
Casters: stand back and cast at an appropriate rate. Do not cast too fast, or you will be agro'd on. Do not stand close to the mob and cast while poking it with your stupid little dagger, then when you agro the mob run away off into the distance and die. How many casters have I seen do this. How many stars are in the sky. If you want to be a tank, then start a warrior.<br>
<br>
you are a bomber airplane high in the sky dropping devastating blows onto your target, but if you take a few hits then down you go in flames. Stay at max casting range to minimize your affect on the hate list. Do not run out of healing range, do not train the healer with the mob when it comes after you. bring it TO the tanks then stand there. Let the tanks get the mob back. The healers will keep you alive. Dangerous situation? YES so DONT GET INTO IT. Stand back, meter your casting at an appropriate pace. <br>
<br>
&quot;Caster says, 'HEY I died again! Why didnt you heal me?&quot;<br>
&quot;Healer says, &quot;Hmm .. after you cast on the mob like a monkey with a machine gun, you ran out of healing range. I would say you died because you are an ass.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
Special Enchanter stuff: Enchanters can save you. If the puller brings too many or a wandering mob jumps your party during combat the enchanter can remove these mobs from the picture by mezmerizing them. Do not attack mezmerized mobs or agro them with AOE spells or DOTs. When the main tank turns to the mezmerized mobs, again, assist him or her. Before attacking a Mez'd mob, taunt it a lot. Because the mob is mezed he is very very angry at the Enchanter. if you DO NOT taunt first, the mob will instanly jump all over the enchanter instead of the tanks.<br>
<br>
more on this later.<br>
<br>
