<br>
Pulling:  It's not always the best idea to let the tank pull.  Seen a couple of situations in Rathe where it is definitely better to have a tracker &amp; snarer pull, and if there is no ranger, what's left? Right, a druid or bard.  I've seen tanks with minimal Rathe experience get beaten badly, even with SOW.  Same thing with Oggok, if the tank does not know the spawn pattern at all but you do, make sure to explain &amp; show it and pull a couple first to demonstrate.  Letting any zone newbie loose in a area where spawns wander around freely is a surefire way to get your group more than just one or two mobs.  Also, if your shaman is level 50 and your tank is level 40, you may want to reconsider your standard pulling strategy, especially if the shaman is an iksar or troll. (ok, this one's a &quot;Doh&quot;, sorry ))<br>
<br>
Taunting: This might be another &quot;Doh&quot;, but I just had the chance to try it out recently and am still quite astonished at how well &quot;Blinding Flash&quot; works as a taunting tool for Paladins.  So no more excuses like &quot;I couldn't taunt him off!&quot; .. )<br>
<br>
Roles:  Yup, know your role, but be also aware that you may have to exhibit some instant flexibility.  It's sometimes those flashes of creativity that saves the group's life.  A druid friend of mine had to evac once out of a kunark dungeon and landed in the Emerald Jungle with the Kunark-dungeon only evac.  Lo and behold, a big mob jumped on then at their arrival...what would you do?  Ok, the best thing would have been to mem only the evac you know best (I heard the first one, Succor: BB, has always the highest success rate, but it's not confirmed), but also be prepared to either yell at someone else to evacc or sit down and memm another one.  <br>
